  <static seed="1593" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations55.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {-\frac{6}{y}+\frac{8}{y-5}} = 1 }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{10,-3\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of fractions, we multiply each term in this equation by the common denominator, which is <m>{y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)}</m> in this example.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp {-\frac{6}{y}+\frac{8}{y-5}} = 1 \\
   \amp {-\frac{6}{y}y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)+\frac{8}{y-5}y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)} ={y\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)} \\
   \amp {-6\mathopen{}\left(y-5\right)+8y} = {y^{2}-5y} \\
   \amp {-6y+30+8y} = {y^{2}-5y} \\
   \amp {2y+30} = {y^{2}-5y} \\
   \amp {2y+30-y^{2}+5y} = 0 \\
   \amp {-y^{2}+7y+30} = 0 \\
   \amp -({y^{2}-7y-30})=0 \\
   \amp -({y+3})({y-10})=0 \\
   \amp {y+3}=0 \:\: or\:\: {y-10}=0 \\
   \amp y={-3} \:\: or\:\: y={10}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p><alert>Checking</alert></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \amp y = 0 \amp \;\amp  y - 5=0 \\
   \amp y=0 \amp \;\amp  y=5
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must exclude <m>0</m> and <m>5</m> from the solution set. There is no conflict with those two solutions we got, so the final solution is <m>y={-3}</m> and <m>y={10}</m>.</p>
</solution>
